{"title_page": "Elliot Stabler", "text_new": "{{short description|Fictional character on Law & Order: Special Victims Unit}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{in-universe|date=September 2015}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name        = Elliot Stabler\n| series      = [[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]\n| image       = [[File:Elliot Stabler - SVU.png|250px]]\n| first       = \"[[Payback (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|Payback]]\"\n| last        = \"[[Smoked (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|Smoked]]\"\n| portrayer   = [[Christopher Meloni]]\n| family      = '''Wife:''' [[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Kathy Stabler|Kathy Stabler]]<br> '''Children:'''<br> Maureen Stabler (daughter) <br> Kathleen Stabler (daughter) <br> Richard \"Dickie\" Stabler (son) <br> Elizabeth \"Lizzie\" Stabler (daughter) <br> Elliot \"Eli\" Stabler Jr. (son) <br> '''Parents:''' Joseph Stabler (father, deceased)  <br>  Bernadette Stabler (mother) <br> '''Siblings:''' three brothers<br/>two sisters<ref name=\"Hate\"/>\n| title       = [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] Detective 1st Grade\n| lbl21       = Partner\n| data21      = [[Olivia Benson]]<br/>[[Donald Cragen]]<br/>[[Anthony Anderson|Lucius Blaine]]<ref name=Blaine /> (temporary)<br>[[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Danielle Beck|Danielle Beck]] (temporary)\n| lbl22       = Seasons\n| data22      = '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 1)|1]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 2)|2]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 3)|3]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 4)|4]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 5)|5]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 6)|6]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 7)|7]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)|8]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 9)|9]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 10)|10]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 11)|11]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 12)|12]]'''\n}}\n'''Elliot Stabler''' is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] portrayed by [[Christopher Meloni]] and one of the lead characters on the [[NBC]] [[police procedural]] series ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' during the first 12 seasons. As a result of Meloni's sudden departure from the cast at the end of the twelfth season, Stabler abruptly retires from the police force off-screen during the Season 13 premiere. In April 2020, it was announced that Meloni would reprise the role for a new ''SVU''-spinoff series<ref name=\"CNN-spinoff\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/entertainment/stabler-meloni-law-and-order-svu-spin-off/index.html|title=Elliot Stabler is back in a 'Law & Order: SVU' spin-off|first=Madeline|last=Holcombe|website=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting Systems]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>, where Stabler comes out of retirement to lead an NYPD organized crime task force.\n\n==Character overview==\nStabler is an [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] [[New York City Police Department#Rank structure|detective 1st Grade]] with [[Manhattan]]'s 16th Precinct, which investigates [[Sex and the law|sex crime]]s. He joined the NYPD in 1986<ref name=\"Wrong is Right\">{{Cite episode |title=Wrong is Right |series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit |series-link= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]] |date=October 20, 2000 |season= 2 |number= 1}}</ref> and became a detective with the SVU in 1993<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Rooftop |series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit |series-link= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]] |date=October 19, 2001|season= 3 |number= 4}}</ref>, where he has been partnered with [[Olivia Benson|Detective Olivia Benson]] ([[Mariska Hargitay]]) for approximately one year prior to the time-frame of the show's first episode. Stabler is dedicated to his job but often takes cases personally, thus affecting his judgment. Nonetheless, Stabler has a 97% case-closure rate as of 2007.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Haystack|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=February 20, 2007|season=8|number=15}}</ref> His badge number is 6313.<ref name=\"Hate\">{{Cite episode|title=Hate|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=January 13, 2004|season=5|number=13}}</ref><ref name=\"ripped\"/>\n\nStabler is [[Irish American]]<ref name=\"Hate\"/> and lives at 72-12 Castleside Street, [[Glen Oaks, Queens]] with his wife Kathy ([[Isabel Gillies]]) and five children (Maureen, Kathleen, Richard \"Dickie\", Elizabeth \"Lizzie\", and Elliot \"Eli\" Jr.). Stabler was born October 20, 1966.<ref name=\"Hate\"/> He is devoted to his family and frequently mentions or thinks about them while working cases. He is also a practicing [[Catholic]] whose faith sometimes complicates the cases on which he works.\n\nSeries creator [[Dick Wolf]] named ''SVU''{{'}}s two lead detectives after his son, Elliot, and his daughter, Olivia.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/dick-wolf/bio/194137 |title=Dick Wolf: Biography|magazine=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]]}}</ref> Executive producer and head writer [[Neal Baer]] has explained that, in contrast to Benson - \"the empathetic, passionate voice for these victims\"-<ref name=\"msn\">{{cite web|first=Greg|last=David|url=http://entertainment1.sympatico.msn.ca/TV_Guide/Interviews/Insider/Articles/190207_mariskahargitay_GD|title=Law & Order: SVU's Mariska Hargitay speaks!|website=[[MSN]]|date=February 19, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2009|archivedate=February 6, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206234616/http://entertainment1.sympatico.msn.ca/TV_Guide/Interviews/Insider/Articles/190207_mariskahargitay_GD}}</ref> Stabler embodies \"the rage we feel, the 'How can this happen?' feeling.\"<ref name=\"msn\"/> Of their partnership, Baer assessed that: \"They both represent the feelings that we feel simultaneously when we hear about these cases. That's why they work so well together.\"<ref name=\"msn\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nStabler was born and raised in [[Bayside, Queens]]. His father, Joseph Stabler, was a policeman who lost his pension and eventually died of [[cancer]]. Stabler had a difficult relationship with his father, who physically and emotionally abused him.<ref name=\"ripped\">{{Cite episode|title=Ripped|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=October 11, 2005|season=7|number=4}}</ref> His mother, Bernadette (n\u00e9e McGinley) ([[Ellen Burstyn]]), has [[bipolar disorder]] and once nearly killed her son during a manic episode. As a result, Stabler has \"erased his childhood\"; he rarely talks about his father and maintains little contact with his mother.<ref name=\"swing\">{{Cite episode|title=Swing|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=October 14, 2008|season=10|number=3}}</ref>\n\nStabler was a [[United States Marine Corps|Marine]] and served in [[Gulf War|Operation Desert Storm]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Goliath|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (Season 6)#ep13|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=NBC|airdate=May 24, 2005|season=6|number=23}}</ref> During his time in the military, he was a [[hand-to-hand combat]] specialist.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Annihilated|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (Season 8)#ep20|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=May 8, 2007|season=8|number=20}}</ref> He also has three [[tattoos]], notably the [[Eagle, Globe, and Anchor]] tattoo on his forearm (the official [[emblem]] of the Marine Corps), and the [[crucifixion of Christ]] on his left [[biceps|bicep]]. One of his best friends died in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"Hate\"/> He has a B.A. from [[Queens College]], which he obtained by going to [[night school|night classes]].<ref name=\"Hate\"/>\n\nStabler harbors a great deal of anger that is sometimes fueled by his job. He is often openly aggressive and intimidating toward suspects, which can either complicate the case further or lead to speedy confessions. When his wife Kathy ([[Isabel Gillies]]) leaves him in Season 6, Stabler's anger rises closer to the surface and in a few episodes threatens to boil over. One such instance occurs when Stabler investigates [[serial killer]] Gordon Rickett ([[Matthew Modine]]), whom he had investigated 14 years earlier. During interrogation, Ricketts tells Stabler that they harbor the same kind of rage, and that if it weren't for his family and his job, Stabler would be just like him. When Benson and Stabler catch Rickett about to murder a young girl, Stabler appears ready to kill him in cold blood; it's only Benson's intervention that prevents him from doing so.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Rage|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=March 1, 2005|season=6|number=17}}</ref>\n\nIn Season 7, he goes to see a police psychiatrist, Dr. Rebecca Hendrix ([[Mary Stuart Masterson]]), after using [[excessive force]] on an abusive parent. Stabler eventually opens up to Hendrix about his personal demons,<ref name=\"ripped\" /> and they become close until Hendrix is transferred.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Philadelphia|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=February 27, 2007|season=8|number=16}}</ref> By Season 9, he and Kathy reconcile, and Stabler learns to better deal with his problems.\n\nIn the Season 12 finale, Stabler is forced to shoot and kill a young woman who opens fire in the Special Victims squad room. Before dying in Stabler's arms, she had killed two suspects involved in the rape and murder of her mother and injured a third, as well as killing recurring character [[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Sister Peg|Sister Peg]] ([[Charlayne Woodard]]).<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Smoked|episodelink=Smoked (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=May 18, 2011|season=12|number=24}}</ref> After the shootout, Stabler is placed on [[administrative leave]] by the NYPD's Internal Affairs Bureau.<ref>{{Cite web|first1=Adam|last1=Bryant|first2=Natalie|last2=Abrams|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Mega-Buzz-NCIS-Fringe-SVU-1036910.aspx|title=Mega Buzz: Tiva Time on NCIS? Plus: Fringe's Future and Stabler's SVU Exit |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |publisher=NTVB Media|location=New York City|date=August 30, 2011|accessdate=February 25, 2018}}</ref> Although he is eventually cleared, this shooting is the sixth such incident in his NYPD career. His superior, Captain [[Donald Cragen]] ([[Dann Florek]]), comments that if Stabler wants to keep his job, he will have to undergo a psychological evaluation, take an anger management class, and submit to a review of his entire personnel file by the IAB. Benson is confident that Stabler will not agree to these terms, and he proves her right by retiring from the force off-screen during the Season 13 premiere.<ref name=\"ScorchedEarth\">{{Cite episode|title=Scorched Earth|episodelink=Scorched Earth (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=September 21, 2011|season=13|number=1}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe married his wife, [[Kathy Stabler|Kathy]] ([[Isabel Gillies]]), when they were both 17 years old, and at the beginning of the series, they have four school-aged children: Maureen ([[Erin Broderick]]), Kathleen (Alison Siko), and twins Richard \"Dickie\" ([[Jeffrey Scaperrotta]]), and Elizabeth \"Lizzie\". Richard (he stopped using his nickname upon entering adolescence) is named after Col. Richard Finley ([[James Brolin]]), Stabler's former commanding officer in the Marines, whom Stabler later arrests after discovering that he murdered a woman.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Lunacy|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=October 21, 2008|season=10|number=4}}</ref>\n\nAfter years of the stress involved with being married to a police officer, Kathy leaves Stabler, taking their children, and temporarily moves in with her mother.<ref name=\"doubt\">{{Cite episode |title=Doubt|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: SVU|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate= November 23, 2004|season= 6|number= 8}}</ref> Following a case involving a divorce that turned violent, Stabler signs the [[divorce]] papers, saying, \"when love warps to hate, there's nothing you won't do.\"<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Burned|series=Law & Order: SVU|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=January 8, 2007|season=8|number=11}}</ref> However, after being cleared in the death of a suspect, Stabler realizes that he cannot bear to lose either his job or his family, so he seeks reconciliation with his wife.<ref name=\"sin\">{{Cite episode |title=Dependent|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate= February 13, 2007|season= 8|number= 14}}</ref> A short time later, Kathy announces that she is [[pregnant]] and asks Stabler to come home.<ref name=\"screwed\">{{Cite episode |title=Screwed|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate= May 22, 2007|season= 8|number= 22}}</ref> After a serious car accident, Kathy delivers a healthy baby boy, Elliot Stabler Jr. (Eli) (born November 17, 2007). Kathy nearly dies as a result of the crash, but paramedics are able to save her.<ref name=\"paternity\">{{Cite episode |title=Paternity|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate= November 27, 2007|season= 9|number= 9}}</ref>\n\nOf his five children, Kathleen and Dickie have most directly affected his job. Kathleen is twice charged with [[DUI]];<ref name=\"screwed\" /> he uses his clout as a police officer to make the first charge disappear, but he eventually realizes that he has to let her face the consequences of her actions, and she is sentenced to [[community service]].<ref name=\"alternate\">{{Cite episode |title=Alternate|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|credits= |network= NBC|airdate= September 25, 2007|season= 9|number= 1}}</ref> Kathleen then steals her father's [[credit card]] and gives it to her boyfriend, who rings up thousands of dollars in charges.<ref name=\"trials\">{{Cite episode |title=Trials|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate= September 23, 2008|season= 10|number= 1}}</ref> She is later arrested for [[Burglary|breaking and entering]] and [[robbery]], at which time doctors and her family realize that she suffers from [[bipolar disorder]], which is a condition she shares with her paternal grandmother, Bernadette. When she faces prison time, Stabler reaches out to his mother for the first time in three years and asks her to tell Kathleen about her illness so she will get help. After speaking with her grandmother, Kathleen agrees to treatment.<ref name=\"swing\" /> She later becomes an advocate for sexual assault victims, and in one episode, helps her father on a case.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Gray|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=November 17, 2010|season=12|number=9}}</ref>\n\nDickie also occasionally gives his father problems. In a Season 11 episode, he runs away from school and tries to join the [[United States Army|Army]], something Stabler disapproves of. It later turns out that Dickie is acting out because his friend, Shane, has been murdered. Stabler refuses to sign a parental consent form for Dickie to join the Army, but resolves to be a more attentive parent.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Turmoil|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=November 11, 2009|season=11|number=8}}</ref>\n\nStabler is fiercely protective of his children and becomes defensive if a suspect asks about his family; it is suggested that he sees aspects of his children in every victim. As a result, he harbors an intense hatred of [[pedophilia|pedophiles]], admitting to a police psychiatrist that he sometimes [[fantasy (psychology)|fantasizes]] about killing them.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Slaves|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=May 19, 2000|season=1|number=22}}</ref> He almost loses his job as a result.<ref name=\"Wrong is Right\"/> In a later episode, he beats up a pedophile ([[Tom Noonan]]) who posts a picture of his daughter Elizabeth on his website.<ref name=\"Confession\">{{Cite episode |title=Confession|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: SVU|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate= September 30, 2008|season= 10|number= 2}}</ref>\n\nStabler has occasionally seen aspects of himself in a [[child abuse]]r; during one case, the actions of an abusive parent prompt him to recall an incident in which he lost his temper and raised his hand to slap his daughter Maureen, who was a toddler at the time.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Shaken|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=March 25, 2003|season=5|number=10}}</ref>\n\nChild victims tend to respond to him. For example, Stabler successfully reaches out to a 15-year-old girl ([[Rachael Bella]]) who [[Regression (psychology)|regresses]] to a childlike state after being attacked by her father. SVU's resident psychiatrist, Dr. [[George Huang (Law & Order)|George Huang]] ([[B.D. Wong]]), theorizes that only Stabler would be able to reach her, as he is a father, and she is looking for a father figure.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Resilience|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=December 6, 2002|season=4|number=10}}</ref>\n\n==Partners==\n\n===Olivia Benson===\nStabler is partnered with Olivia Benson for 12 years. They are best friends, and trust each other completely. Stabler is Benson's longest relationship with a man,<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Futility|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate=April 25, 2003|season=4|number=22}}</ref> and they have even each promised to give the other a kidney should they need a transplant.<ref name=\"paternity\"/>\n\nTheir relationship is not without friction, however. The two sometimes argue over the cases they work on; Benson tends to be quicker to side with the victims. For example, during a case in which three women are charged with raping a male [[stripper]], Benson and ADA [[Alexandra Cabot]] ([[Stephanie March]]) believe the man's story, while Stabler takes a cynical view of his claim from the start.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Ridicule|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=December 14, 2001|season=3|number=10}}</ref>\n\nBenson and Stabler are separated at times during the show. She asks for a new partner after Stabler expects her to jeopardize his life to shoot a convicted sex offender ([[Lou Diamond Phillips]]) who had kidnapped two children and killed one of them.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Fault|series=Law & Order: SVU|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=April 4, 2006|season=7|number=19}}</ref> Instead, she is briefly reassigned to computer crimes and replaced by a Queens SVU detective, Lucius Blaine ([[Anthony Anderson]]).<ref name=Blaine>{{Cite episode|title=Fat|series=Law & Order: SVU|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=May 2, 2006|season=7|number=20}}</ref> Benson and Stabler become partners again in the eighth season.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Choreographed|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=November 28, 2006|season=8|number=9}}</ref> They remain partners for the rest of Stabler's time in the precinct.\n\nIn the Season 12 episode \"Merchandise,\" Benson and Stabler are temporarily appointed as [[United States Marshals Service|Special Deputy U.S. Marshals]] so they can arrest the leaders of a [[human trafficking]] operation located outside their jurisdiction. Once the criminals are in custody, they turn in the badges and take up their positions in SVU again.\n\n===Dani Beck===\nStabler is assigned a temporary partner named [[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Danielle Beck|Dani Beck]] ([[Connie Nielsen]]) while Benson is undercover in Oregon, embedded in an [[eco-terrorism|eco-terrorist]] group at the request of the FBI in season 8 ([[Mariska Hargitay]] was pregnant and on [[maternity leave]]). Beck takes well to the job, and she and Stabler become close. There is also some sexual tension between the two, and during one case, they share a kiss.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Underbelly|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep7|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=November 14, 2006|season=8|number=7}}</ref> The relationship goes no further, however, as Beck leaves when she realizes that she will not be able to save every victim.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Cage|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep8|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=November 21, 2006|season=8|number=8}}</ref>\n\n===Jo Marlowe===\n[[Jo Marlowe]] (played by [[Sharon Stone]]) was Stabler's training officer. She is appointed by District Attorney [[Jack McCoy]] ([[Sam Waterston]]) to be the new ADA for the SVU squad during a four-episode run in Season 11. Stabler reveals that he has not seen her for 15 years when she first arrives as the new ADA. Marlowe was a lieutenant in 1995 when she left the NYPD after her command decision resulted in the deaths of two of her officers.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Ace|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate=May 5, 2010|season=11|number=22}}</ref> She was diagnosed with an \"aggressive\" type of [[breast cancer]] and had a [[mastectomy|bilateral radical mastectomy]] a year before joining the SVU squad.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Shattered|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=May 19, 2010|season=11|number=24}}</ref>\n\n==Development and casting==\nFor the role of Stabler, the finalists were Meloni, [[Tim Matheson]], and [[John Slattery]]. Meloni and Hargitay had auditioned in the final round together, and after the actors left, there was a moment of dead silence, after which Wolf blurted out, \"Oh well. There's no doubt who we should choose \u2013 Hargitay and Meloni.\" The duo, who Wolf believed had the perfect chemistry from the first time he saw them together, were his first choice. [[Garth Ancier]], head of NBC, agreed, and the rest of the panel assembled voiced their assent.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Susan|last1=Green|first2=Randee|last2=Dawn |title=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit Unofficial Companion |publisher=BenBella Books, Inc|location=Dallas, Texas|date=2009|page=11|isbn=978-1-933771-88-5}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, after the show's [[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 10)|tenth season]], Hargitay and Meloni's contracts expired when they were reportedly making $375,000<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Michael|last=Schneider|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118005510|title=Meloni, Hargitay seal deal with 'SVU'|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=June 29, 2009|accessdate=February 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62deCkQDZ?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118005510|archivedate=October 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\u2013$385,000 per episode.<ref name=\"la pay\">{{cite news|first=Denise|last=Martin|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/06/law-order-svu-stars-christopher-meloni-and-mariska-hargitay-sign-on-for-two-more-years.html|title='Law & Order: SVU' stars Christopher Meloni and Mariska Hargitay sign on for two more years|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=June 29, 2009|accessdate=February 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62deFlGUW?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/04/08/svu-exclusive-n/|archivedate=October 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> During negotiations in April for a new contract, the actors attempted to receive a percentage of the show's profits. It was rumored that NBC threatened to replace Hargitay and Meloni if they persisted in their demands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/04/08/svu-exclusive-n/|title='SVU' exclusive: NBC to replace Chris and Mariska?!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=April 8, 2009|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|accessdate=February 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62deFlGUW?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/04/08/svu-exclusive-n/|archivedate=October 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Two months later, however, it was officially reported that both their contracts had been renewed for two more years.<ref name=\"la pay\"/>\n\n==Departure==\nIn May 2011, Meloni announced that he would not be returning to ''SVU'' in fall 2011 for its 13th season after the failure of negotiations over a new contract.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Natalie|last=Abrams|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Christopher-Meloni-Exits-SVU-1033486.aspx |title=Christopher Meloni Exits Law & Order: SVU|magazine=[[TV Guide]] |publisher=NTVB Media|location=New York City|date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref> The Stabler character was subsequently written out of the show.<ref>{{cite news|first=Bill|last=Carter|url=https://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/05/24/christopher-meloni-to-leave-law-order-svu/|title=Christopher Meloni to Leave 'Law & Order: SVU'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|date=May 24, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Spinoff series==\nOn March 31, 2020, NBC announced that it had ordered a 13 episode series with [[Christopher Meloni]] reprising his role as Elliot Stabler in an as-yet-untitled drama series, produced by [[Dick Wolf]]. The series will center around an organized crime taskforce headed by Stabler.<ref name=\"CNN-spinoff\"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/christopher-meloni-returns-new-dick-wolf-series-elliot-stabler-nbc-law-order-svu-1202896323/|title=Christopher Meloni As 'SVU' Character Elliot Stabler To Headline New Dick Wolf Drama Series For NBC|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite magazine|first=Jessica|last=Wang|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/elliot-stabler-is-back-for-nbcs-law-order-svu-spinoff-22680671|title=Elliot Stabler Is Back For NBC's 'Law & Order: SVU' Spinoff|magazine=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|publisher=Bustle Digital Group|location=New York City|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Acclaim==\nMeloni was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] in 2006, in the category of Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series, for his role as Elliot Stabler.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Ileane|last=Rudolph|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/christopher-meloni-preps-41212/|title=Christopher Meloni Preps for the Emmys|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|publisher=NTVB Media|location=New York City|date=August 22, 2006|accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\nThe following are the medals and service awards worn by Elliot Stabler, as seen in \"Dolls.\"\n\n{|\n|[[File:American Flag Breast Bar.jpg|100px]]\n|[[Medals of the New York City Police Department#American Flag Breast Bar|American Flag Breast Bar]]\n|-\n|[[Image:NYPD Medal of Honor breast bar.svg|100px]]\n|[[New York City Police Department Medal of Honor|NYPD Medal of Honor]]\n|-\n|[[File:Unit Citation.jpg|100px]]\n|[[Medals of the New York City Police Department#Unit Citation|NYPD Unit Citation Bar]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law & Order: Special Victims Unit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stabler, Elliot}}\n[[Category:Fictional characters from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fictional Gulf War veterans]]\n[[Category:Fictional New York City Police Department detectives]]\n[[Category:Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Marine Corps personnel]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1999]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of child abuse]]\n[[Category:Crossover characters in television]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional character on Law & Order: Special Victims Unit}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{in-universe|date=September 2015}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name        = Elliot Stabler\n| series      = [[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]\n| image       = [[File:Elliot Stabler - SVU.png|250px]]\n| first       = \"[[Payback (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|Payback]]\"\n| last        = \"[[Smoked (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|Smoked]]\"\n| portrayer   = [[Christopher Meloni]]\n| family      = '''Wife:''' [[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Kathy Stabler|Kathy Stabler]]<br> '''Children:'''<br> Maureen Stabler (daughter) <br> Kathleen Stabler (daughter) <br> Richard \"Dickie\" Stabler (son) <br> Elizabeth \"Lizzie\" Stabler (daughter) <br> Elliot \"Eli\" Stabler Jr. (son) <br> '''Parents:''' Joseph Stabler (father, deceased)  <br>  Bernadette Stabler (mother) <br> '''Siblings:''' three brothers<br/>two sisters<ref name=\"Hate\"/>\n| title       = [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] Detective 1st Grade\n| lbl21       = Partner\n| data21      = [[Olivia Benson]]<br/>[[Donald Cragen]]<br/>[[Anthony Anderson|Lucius Blaine]]<ref name=Blaine /> (temporary)<br>[[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Danielle Beck|Danielle Beck]] (temporary)\n| lbl22       = Seasons\n| data22      = '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 1)|1]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 2)|2]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 3)|3]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 4)|4]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 5)|5]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 6)|6]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 7)|7]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)|8]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 9)|9]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 10)|10]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 11)|11]]''', '''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 12)|12]]'''\n}}\n'''Elliot Stabler''' is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] portrayed by [[Christopher Meloni]] and one of the lead characters on the [[NBC]] [[police procedural]] series ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' during the first 12 seasons. As a result of Meloni's sudden departure from the cast at the end of the twelfth season, Stabler abruptly retires from the police force off-screen during the Season 13 premiere. In April 2020, it was announced that Meloni would reprise the role for a new ''SVU''-spinoff series<ref name=\"CNN-spinoff\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/01/entertainment/stabler-meloni-law-and-order-svu-spin-off/index.html|title=Elliot Stabler is back in a 'Law & Order: SVU' spin-off|first=Madeline|last=Holcombe|website=[[CNN]]|publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting Systems]]|location=Atlanta, Georgia|date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>, where Stabler comes out of retirement to lead an NYPD organized crime task force.\n\n==Character overview==\nStabler is an [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] [[New York City Police Department#Rank structure|detective 1st Grade]] with [[Manhattan]]'s 16th Precinct, which investigates [[Sex and the law|sex crime]]s. He joined the NYPD in 1986<ref name=\"Wrong is Right\">{{Cite episode |title=Wrong is Right |series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit |series-link= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]] |date=October 20, 2000 |season= 2 |number= 1}}</ref> and became a detective with the SVU in 1993<ref>{{Cite episode |title=Rooftop |series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit |series-link= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]] |date=October 19, 2001|season= 3 |number= 4}}</ref>, where he has been partnered with [[Olivia Benson|Detective Olivia Benson]] ([[Mariska Hargitay]]) for approximately one year prior to the time-frame of the show's first episode. Stabler is dedicated to his job but often takes cases personally, thus affecting his judgment. Nonetheless, Stabler has a 97% case-closure rate as of 2007.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Haystack|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=February 20, 2007|season=8|number=15}}</ref> His badge number is 6313.<ref name=\"Hate\">{{Cite episode|title=Hate|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=January 13, 2004|season=5|number=13}}</ref><ref name=\"ripped\"/>\n\nStabler is [[Irish American]]<ref name=\"Hate\"/> and lives at 72-12 Castleside Street, [[Glen Oaks, Queens]] with his wife Kathy ([[Isabel Gillies]]) and five children (Maureen, Kathleen, Richard \"Dickie\", Elizabeth \"Lizzie\", and Elliot \"Eli\" Jr.). Stabler was born October 20, 1966.<ref name=\"Hate\"/> He is devoted to his family and frequently mentions or thinks about them while working cases. He is also a practicing [[Catholic]] whose faith sometimes complicates the cases on which he works.\n\nSeries creator [[Dick Wolf]] named ''SVU''{{'}}s two lead detectives after his son, Elliot, and his daughter, Olivia.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/dick-wolf/bio/194137 |title=Dick Wolf: Biography|magazine=[[TV Guide|TVGuide.com]]}}</ref> Executive producer and head writer [[Neal Baer]] has explained that, in contrast to Benson - \"the empathetic, passionate voice for these victims\"-<ref name=\"msn\">{{cite web|first=Greg|last=David|url=http://entertainment1.sympatico.msn.ca/TV_Guide/Interviews/Insider/Articles/190207_mariskahargitay_GD|title=Law & Order: SVU's Mariska Hargitay speaks!|website=[[MSN]]|date=February 19, 2007|accessdate=May 12, 2009|archivedate=February 6, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206234616/http://entertainment1.sympatico.msn.ca/TV_Guide/Interviews/Insider/Articles/190207_mariskahargitay_GD}}</ref> Stabler embodies \"the rage we feel, the 'How can this happen?' feeling.\"<ref name=\"msn\"/> Of their partnership, Baer assessed that: \"They both represent the feelings that we feel simultaneously when we hear about these cases. That's why they work so well together.\"<ref name=\"msn\"/>\n\n==Biography==\nStabler was born and raised in [[Bayside, Queens]]. His father, Joseph Stabler, was a policeman who lost his pension and eventually died of [[cancer]]. Stabler had a difficult relationship with his father, who physically and emotionally abused him.<ref name=\"ripped\">{{Cite episode|title=Ripped|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=October 11, 2005|season=7|number=4}}</ref> His mother, Bernadette (n\u00e9e McGinley) ([[Ellen Burstyn]]), has [[bipolar disorder]] and once nearly killed her son during a manic episode. As a result, Stabler has \"erased his childhood\"; he rarely talks about his father and maintains little contact with his mother.<ref name=\"swing\">{{Cite episode|title=Swing|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=October 14, 2008|season=10|number=3}}</ref>\n\nStabler was a [[United States Marine Corps|Marine]] and served in [[Gulf War|Operation Desert Storm]].<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Goliath|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (Season 6)#ep13|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=NBC|airdate=May 24, 2005|season=6|number=23}}</ref> During his time in the military, he was a [[hand-to-hand combat]] specialist.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Annihilated|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (Season 8)#ep20|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=May 8, 2007|season=8|number=20}}</ref> He also has three [[tattoos]], notably the [[Eagle, Globe, and Anchor]] tattoo on his forearm (the official [[emblem]] of the Marine Corps), and the [[crucifixion of Christ]] on his left [[biceps|bicep]]. One of his best friends died in the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref name=\"Hate\"/> He has a B.A. from [[Queens College]], which he obtained by going to [[night school|night classes]].<ref name=\"Hate\"/>\n\nStabler harbors a great deal of anger that is sometimes fueled by his job. He is often openly aggressive and intimidating toward suspects, which can either complicate the case further or lead to speedy confessions. When his wife Kathy ([[Isabel Gillies]]) leaves him in Season 6, Stabler's anger rises closer to the surface and in a few episodes threatens to boil over. One such instance occurs when Stabler investigates [[serial killer]] Gordon Rickett ([[Matthew Modine]]), whom he had investigated 14 years earlier. During interrogation, Ricketts tells Stabler that they harbor the same kind of rage, and that if it weren't for his family and his job, Stabler would be just like him. When Benson and Stabler catch Rickett about to murder a young girl, Stabler appears ready to kill him in cold blood; it's only Benson's intervention that prevents him from doing so.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Rage|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=March 1, 2005|season=6|number=17}}</ref>\n\nIn Season 7, he goes to see a police psychiatrist, Dr. Rebecca Hendrix ([[Mary Stuart Masterson]]), after using [[excessive force]] on an abusive parent. Stabler eventually opens up to Hendrix about his personal demons,<ref name=\"ripped\" /> and they become close until Hendrix is transferred.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Philadelphia|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=February 27, 2007|season=8|number=16}}</ref> By Season 9, he and Kathy reconcile, and Stabler learns to better deal with his problems.\n\nIn the Season 12 finale, Stabler is forced to shoot and kill a young woman who opens fire in the Special Victims squad room. Before dying in Stabler's arms, she had killed two suspects involved in the rape and murder of her mother and injured a third, as well as killing recurring character [[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Sister Peg|Sister Peg]] ([[Charlayne Woodard]]).<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Smoked|episodelink=Smoked (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=May 18, 2011|season=12|number=24}}</ref> After the shootout, Stabler is placed on [[administrative leave]] by the NYPD's Internal Affairs Bureau.<ref>{{Cite web|first1=Adam|last1=Bryant|first2=Natalie|last2=Abrams|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Mega-Buzz-NCIS-Fringe-SVU-1036910.aspx|title=Mega Buzz: Tiva Time on NCIS? Plus: Fringe's Future and Stabler's SVU Exit |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |publisher=NTVB Media|location=New York City|date=August 30, 2011|accessdate=February 25, 2018}}</ref> Although he is eventually cleared, this shooting is the sixth such incident in his NYPD career. His superior, Captain [[Donald Cragen]] ([[Dann Florek]]), comments that if Stabler wants to keep his job, he will have to undergo a psychological evaluation, take an anger management class, and submit to a review of his entire personnel file by the IAB. Benson is confident that Stabler will not agree to these terms, and he proves her right by retiring from the force off-screen during the Season 13 premiere.<ref name=\"ScorchedEarth\">{{Cite episode|title=Scorched Earth|episodelink=Scorched Earth (Law & Order: Special Victims Unit)|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=September 21, 2011|season=13|number=1}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHe married his wife, [[Kathy Stabler|Kathy]] ([[Isabel Gillies]]), when they were both 17 years old, and at the beginning of the series, they have four school-aged children: Maureen ([[Erin Broderick]]), Kathleen (Alison Siko), and twins Richard \"Dickie\" ([[Jeffrey Scaperrotta]]), and Elizabeth \"Lizzie\". Richard (he stopped using his nickname upon entering adolescence) is named after Col. Richard Finley ([[James Brolin]]), Stabler's former commanding officer in the Marines, whom Stabler later arrests after discovering that he murdered a woman.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Lunacy|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=October 21, 2008|season=10|number=4}}</ref>\n\nAfter years of the stress involved with being married to a police officer, Kathy leaves Stabler, taking their children, and temporarily moves in with her mother.<ref name=\"doubt\">{{Cite episode |title=Doubt|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: SVU|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate= November 23, 2004|season= 6|number= 8}}</ref> Following a case involving a divorce that turned violent, Stabler signs the [[divorce]] papers, saying, \"when love warps to hate, there's nothing you won't do.\"<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Burned|series=Law & Order: SVU|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=January 8, 2007|season=8|number=11}}</ref> However, after being cleared in the death of a suspect, Stabler realizes that he cannot bear to lose either his job or his family, so he seeks reconciliation with his wife.<ref name=\"sin\">{{Cite episode |title=Dependent|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate= February 13, 2007|season= 8|number= 14}}</ref> A short time later, Kathy announces that she is [[pregnant]] and asks Stabler to come home.<ref name=\"screwed\">{{Cite episode |title=Screwed|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate= May 22, 2007|season= 8|number= 22}}</ref> After a serious car accident, Kathy delivers a healthy baby boy, Elliot Stabler Jr. (Eli) (born November 17, 2007). Kathy nearly dies as a result of the crash, but paramedics are able to save her.<ref name=\"paternity\">{{Cite episode |title=Paternity|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate= November 27, 2007|season= 9|number= 9}}</ref>\n\nOf his five children, Kathleen and Dickie have most directly affected his job. Kathleen is twice charged with [[DUI]];<ref name=\"screwed\" /> he uses his clout as a police officer to make the first charge disappear, but he eventually realizes that he has to let her face the consequences of her actions, and she is sentenced to [[community service]].<ref name=\"alternate\">{{Cite episode |title=Alternate|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|credits= |network= NBC|airdate= September 25, 2007|season= 9|number= 1}}</ref> Kathleen then steals her father's [[credit card]] and gives it to her boyfriend, who rings up thousands of dollars in charges.<ref name=\"trials\">{{Cite episode |title=Trials|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate= September 23, 2008|season= 10|number= 1}}</ref> She is later arrested for [[Burglary|breaking and entering]] and [[robbery]], at which time doctors and her family realize that she suffers from [[bipolar disorder]], which is a condition she shares with her paternal grandmother, Bernadette. When she faces prison time, Stabler reaches out to his mother for the first time in three years and asks her to tell Kathleen about her illness so she will get help. After speaking with her grandmother, Kathleen agrees to treatment.<ref name=\"swing\" /> She later becomes an advocate for sexual assault victims, and in one episode, helps her father on a case.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Gray|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=November 17, 2010|season=12|number=9}}</ref>\n\nDickie also occasionally gives his father problems. In a Season 11 episode, he runs away from school and tries to join the [[United States Army|Army]], something Stabler disapproves of. It later turns out that Dickie is acting out because his friend, Shane, has been murdered. Stabler refuses to sign a parental consent form for Dickie to join the Army, but resolves to be a more attentive parent.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Turmoil|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=November 11, 2009|season=11|number=8}}</ref>\n\nStabler is fiercely protective of his children and becomes defensive if a suspect asks about his family; it is suggested that he sees aspects of his children in every victim. As a result, he harbors an intense hatred of [[pedophilia|pedophiles]], admitting to a police psychiatrist that he sometimes [[fantasy (psychology)|fantasizes]] about killing them.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Slaves|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=May 19, 2000|season=1|number=22}}</ref> He almost loses his job as a result.<ref name=\"Wrong is Right\"/> In a later episode, he beats up a pedophile ([[Tom Noonan]]) who posts a picture of his daughter Elizabeth on his website.<ref name=\"Confession\">{{Cite episode |title=Confession|episodelink= |series= Law & Order: SVU|serieslink= Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate= September 30, 2008|season= 10|number= 2}}</ref>\n\nStabler has occasionally seen aspects of himself in a [[child abuse]]r; during one case, the actions of an abusive parent prompt him to recall an incident in which he lost his temper and raised his hand to slap his daughter Maureen, who was a toddler at the time.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Shaken|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=March 25, 2003|season=5|number=10}}</ref>\n\nChild victims tend to respond to him. For example, Stabler successfully reaches out to a 15-year-old girl ([[Rachael Bella]]) who [[Regression (psychology)|regresses]] to a childlike state after being attacked by her father. SVU's resident psychiatrist, Dr. [[George Huang (Law & Order)|George Huang]] ([[B.D. Wong]]), theorizes that only Stabler would be able to reach her, as he is a father, and she is looking for a father figure.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Resilience|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=December 6, 2002|season=4|number=10}}</ref>\n\n==Partners==\n\n===Olivia Benson===\nStabler is partnered with Olivia Benson for 12 years. They are best friends, and trust each other completely. Stabler is Benson's longest relationship with a man,<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Futility|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate=April 25, 2003|season=4|number=22}}</ref> and they have even each promised to give the other a kidney should they need a transplant.<ref name=\"paternity\"/>\n\nTheir relationship is not without friction, however. The two sometimes argue over the cases they work on; Benson tends to be quicker to side with the victims. For example, during a case in which three women are charged with raping a male [[stripper]], Benson and ADA [[Alexandra Cabot]] ([[Stephanie March]]) believe the man's story, while Stabler takes a cynical view of his claim from the start.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Ridicule|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=December 14, 2001|season=3|number=10}}</ref>\n\nBenson and Stabler are separated at times during the show. She asks for a new partner after Stabler expects her to jeopardize his life to shoot a convicted sex offender ([[Lou Diamond Phillips]]) who had kidnapped two children and killed one of them.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Fault|series=Law & Order: SVU|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=April 4, 2006|season=7|number=19}}</ref> Instead, she is briefly reassigned to computer crimes and replaced by a Queens SVU detective, Lucius Blaine ([[Anthony Anderson]]).<ref name=Blaine>{{Cite episode|title=Fat|series=Law & Order: SVU|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=May 2, 2006|season=7|number=20}}</ref> Benson and Stabler become partners again in the eighth season.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Choreographed|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=November 28, 2006|season=8|number=9}}</ref> They remain partners for the rest of Stabler's time in the precinct.\n\nIn the Season 12 episode \"Merchandise,\" Benson and Stabler are temporarily appointed as [[United States Marshals Service|Special Deputy U.S. Marshals]] so they can arrest the leaders of a [[human trafficking]] operation located outside their jurisdiction. Once the criminals are in custody, they turn in the badges and take up their positions in SVU again.\n\n===Dani Beck===\nStabler is assigned a temporary partner named [[List of Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters#Danielle Beck|Dani Beck]] ([[Connie Nielsen]]) while Benson is undercover in Oregon, embedded in an [[eco-terrorism|eco-terrorist]] group at the request of the FBI in season 8 ([[Mariska Hargitay]] was pregnant and on [[maternity leave]]). Beck takes well to the job, and she and Stabler become close. There is also some sexual tension between the two, and during one case, they share a kiss.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Underbelly|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep7|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=November 14, 2006|season=8|number=7}}</ref> The relationship goes no further, however, as Beck leaves when she realizes that she will not be able to save every victim.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Cage|episodelink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)#ep8|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network=[[NBC]]|airdate=November 21, 2006|season=8|number=8}}</ref>\n\n===Jo Marlowe===\n[[Jo Marlowe]] (played by [[Sharon Stone]]) was Stabler's training officer. She is appointed by District Attorney [[Jack McCoy]] ([[Sam Waterston]]) to be the new ADA for the SVU squad during a four-episode run in Season 11. Stabler reveals that he has not seen her for 15 years when she first arrives as the new ADA. Marlowe was a lieutenant in 1995 when she left the NYPD after her command decision resulted in the deaths of two of her officers.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Ace|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= NBC|airdate=May 5, 2010|season=11|number=22}}</ref> She was diagnosed with an \"aggressive\" type of [[breast cancer]] and had a [[mastectomy|bilateral radical mastectomy]] a year before joining the SVU squad.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Shattered|series=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|serieslink=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit|network= [[NBC]]|airdate=May 19, 2010|season=11|number=24}}</ref>\n\n==Development and casting==\nFor the role of Stabler, the finalists were Meloni, [[Tim Matheson]], and [[John Slattery]]. Meloni and Hargitay had auditioned in the final round together, and after the actors left, there was a moment of dead silence, after which Wolf blurted out, \"Oh well. There's no doubt who we should choose \u2013 Hargitay and Meloni.\" The duo, who Wolf believed had the perfect chemistry from the first time he saw them together, were his first choice. [[Garth Ancier]], head of NBC, agreed, and the rest of the panel assembled voiced their assent.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Susan|last1=Green|first2=Randee|last2=Dawn |title=Law & Order: Special Victims Unit Unofficial Companion |publisher=BenBella Books, Inc|location=Dallas, Texas|date=2009|page=11|isbn=978-1-933771-88-5}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, after the show's [[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 10)|tenth season]], Hargitay and Meloni's contracts expired when they were reportedly making $375,000<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Michael|last=Schneider|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118005510|title=Meloni, Hargitay seal deal with 'SVU'|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=June 29, 2009|accessdate=February 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62deCkQDZ?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118005510|archivedate=October 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\u2013$385,000 per episode.<ref name=\"la pay\">{{cite news|first=Denise|last=Martin|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/06/law-order-svu-stars-christopher-meloni-and-mariska-hargitay-sign-on-for-two-more-years.html|title='Law & Order: SVU' stars Christopher Meloni and Mariska Hargitay sign on for two more years|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tronc]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=June 29, 2009|accessdate=February 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62deFlGUW?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/04/08/svu-exclusive-n/|archivedate=October 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> During negotiations in April for a new contract, the actors attempted to receive a percentage of the show's profits. It was rumored that NBC threatened to replace Hargitay and Meloni if they persisted in their demands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/04/08/svu-exclusive-n/|title='SVU' exclusive: NBC to replace Chris and Mariska?!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=April 8, 2009|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=New York City|accessdate=February 23, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62deFlGUW?url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2009/04/08/svu-exclusive-n/|archivedate=October 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Two months later, however, it was officially reported that both their contracts had been renewed for two more years.<ref name=\"la pay\"/>\n\n==Departure==\nIn May 2011, Meloni announced that he would not be returning to ''SVU'' in fall 2011 for its 13th season after the failure of negotiations over a new contract.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Natalie|last=Abrams|url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Christopher-Meloni-Exits-SVU-1033486.aspx |title=Christopher Meloni Exits Law & Order: SVU|magazine=[[TV Guide]] |publisher=NTVB Media|location=New York City|date=May 24, 2011 |accessdate=May 24, 2011}}</ref> The Stabler character was subsequently written out of the show.<ref>{{cite news|first=Bill|last=Carter|url=https://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/05/24/christopher-meloni-to-leave-law-order-svu/|title=Christopher Meloni to Leave 'Law & Order: SVU'|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[New York Times Company]]|location=New York City|date=May 24, 2011|accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Spinoff series==\nOn March 31, 2020, NBC announced that it had ordered a 13 episode series with [[Christopher Meloni]] reprising his role as Elliot Stabler in an as-yet-untitled drama series, produced by [[Dick Wolf]]. The series will center around an organized crime taskforce headed by Stabler.<ref name=\"CNN-spinoff\"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/christopher-meloni-returns-new-dick-wolf-series-elliot-stabler-nbc-law-order-svu-1202896323/|title=Christopher Meloni As \u2018SVU\u2019 Character Elliot Stabler To Headline New Dick Wolf Drama Series For NBC|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite magazine|first=Jessica|last=Wang|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/elliot-stabler-is-back-for-nbcs-law-order-svu-spinoff-22680671|title=Elliot Stabler Is Back For NBC\u2019s \u2018Law & Order: SVU\u2019 Spinoff|magazine=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|publisher=Bustle Digital Group|location=New York City|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Acclaim==\nMeloni was nominated for an [[Emmy Award]] in 2006, in the category of Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series, for his role as Elliot Stabler.<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Ileane|last=Rudolph|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/christopher-meloni-preps-41212/|title=Christopher Meloni Preps for the Emmys|magazine=[[TV Guide]]|publisher=NTVB Media|location=New York City|date=August 22, 2006|accessdate=July 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and decorations==\nThe following are the medals and service awards worn by Elliot Stabler, as seen in \"Dolls.\"\n\n{|\n|[[File:American Flag Breast Bar.jpg|100px]]\n|[[Medals of the New York City Police Department#American Flag Breast Bar|American Flag Breast Bar]]\n|-\n|[[Image:NYPD Medal of Honor breast bar.svg|100px]]\n|[[New York City Police Department Medal of Honor|NYPD Medal of Honor]]\n|-\n|[[File:Unit Citation.jpg|100px]]\n|[[Medals of the New York City Police Department#Unit Citation|NYPD Unit Citation Bar]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Law & Order: Special Victims Unit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stabler, Elliot}}\n[[Category:Fictional characters from New York City]]\n[[Category:Fictional Gulf War veterans]]\n[[Category:Fictional New York City Police Department detectives]]\n[[Category:Law & Order: Special Victims Unit characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional United States Marine Corps personnel]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 1999]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of child abuse]]\n[[Category:Crossover characters in television]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Alter: title. | You canuse this toolyourself.Report bugs here. | via #UCB_Gadget", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliot_Stabler"}
{"title_page": "Dov Elbaum", "text_new": "[[File:Dov Elbaum.jpg|thumbnail|Dov Elbaum]]\n'''Dov Elbaum''' ({{lang-he|\u05d3\u05d1 \u05d0\u05dc\u05d1\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd}}; born on 21 December 1970) is an [[Israel]]i writer, editor, journalist, television host and Jewish philosophy lecturer.  \n\n==Biography==\nDov Elbaum was born in Jerusalem's [[Mea She'arim]] neighborhood to an ultra-Orthodox Jewish family. Elbaum is a fifth generation scion of Rabbi [[Yosef Chaim Sonnenfeld]]. He grew up in [[Ramat Eshkol]].<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/magazine/confessions-of-a-religious-anarchist-in-israel-1.428080 Confessions of a religious anarchist, ''[[Haaretz]]]''</ref> He studied at the ultra-Orthodox [[Hebron Yeshiva]] but left the yeshiva and religion after realizing that he did not want to live with the restrictions and isolation from society imposed by the yeshiva's brand of Orthodoxy. After his renunciation of a religious lifestyle, his father cut off contact with him for ten years.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Magazine/Books/Filling-the-void-339143 Filling the void], ''[[Jerusalem Post]]''</ref> He served in the [[Israel Defense Forces]] as a journalist for ''BaMahaneh'', the IDF's weekly magazine. He studied at the [[Adi Lautman Interdisciplinary Programme for Outstanding Students]] of [[Tel-Aviv University]], where he earned an interdisciplinary BA in Philosophy, Kabbalah and Hassidism, and an MA with a research focus on Rabbi [[Nachman of Breslov]]. \n\nElbaum is married to Carmit, has four daughters and lives in [[Kokhav Yair]].\n\n==Journalism and media career==\nFrom 1993-2000, Elbaum wrote extensively for two newspapers, ''Hadashaot'' and ''Yediot Ahronot''. In 2006, he served as editor-in-chief of ''Yediot Ahronot Publishers'' and edited the publisher's flagship project ''People of the Book'', a series celebrating Israel's 60th anniversary. He has edited works by [[Martin Buber]], [[Gershom Scholem]] and others. Elbaum left ''Yediot Ahronot'' Publishers to spend more time writing. He is the author of three novels, ''Zman Elul'' (1997; 2003), ''My Life with the Ancestors'' (2001) and ''Into the Fullness of the Void'' (2007;2009). he has also written three children\u2019s books and numerous essays.\n\nElbaum wrote the script for the weekly television show ''[[Parashat Hashavua]]'' (The Weekly Torah Portion) hosted by Gil Kopatch on channel 1 in 1997. Two years later he wrote the script for the film ''Zakota'', which was broadcast as part of the Wolgin competition at the Jerusalem Film Festival, and aired numerous times on channel 2. This script won first prize of the Council of Culture and Arts of the Ministry of Education.{{CN|date=December 2013}} Between 2001-2005 Elbaum conducted over 700 interviews in the award-winning program, ''Hotzeh Israel'' (Crossing Israel). Later on Elbaum edited and hosted the documentary TV show ''Osim Derech'' (Making Way) on channel 2, which discussed scientists who had won the Israel Price in recent years. Since 2007 Elbaum has been discussing the weekly Torah portion on his TV show ''Mekablim Shabbat'' (Receiving Shabbat) on channel 1, hosting every week different guests (academics, intellectuals, musicians and artists) whose life or field of interest is related to the portion.\n\n==Academic career==\nElbaum has taught at Tel Aviv University, The Open University and Alma College. He was author-in-residence and lecturer at the literature department of [[Ben Gurion University of the Negev]]. Elbaum is a research fellow at the [[Shalom Hartman Institute]]. In 2006, Elbaum established the Secular Yeshiva in southern Tel Aviv in collaboration with [[BINA Center for Jewish Identity and Hebrew Culture]]. The curriculum focuses on intensive study of Jewish texts, from the Bible and Gemara to classic Israeli literature and Zionist history.<ref> BINA {{cite web|url=http://www.bina.org.il/en/programs/yeshiva/about |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224121012/http://www.bina.org.il/en/programs/yeshiva/about |archivedate=2013-12-24 }} </ref> Elbaum teaches a class on Hasidism and Kabbalah at the yeshiva as well as the BINA Center of the Kibbutz Movement in [[Ramat Efal]].  \n\n==Awards and recognition==\nElbaum was awarded the Israel President\u2019s Prize for Young Writers and is the 2013 recipient of the Liebhaber Prize for the Promotion of Religious Tolerance and Cultural Pluralism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dovelbaum.com/index_e.php|title=Dov Elbaum &#124; Homepage|website=www.dovelbaum.com}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n*2003: ''Elul Term''. (1997; 2003) Tel Aviv: Am Oved. During the month of Elul, two weeks before Yom Kippur, when Jewish tradition maintains that God judges man for his sins, Nachman undertakes a regime of penance. He vows himself to silence and later gives up eating and sleeping, devoting himself to sacred study and thoughts of repentance. The purification he longs for confronts a repulsive reality, suffocating, fanatical and fraught with superstition. Elbaum describes the yeshiva world during the seventies and eighties in Jerusalem in a unique language derived from the orthodox Jewish slang. This book was crowned with wonderful reviews and paved Elbaum his literary path within the Israeli society.\n*2001: ''My Life with the Ancestors''. Tel Aviv: Am Oved. An autobiographical fantasy which locates the biblical forefathers in modern Israel. This book was awarded the President's Prize for Young Writers in 2002. \"It is a carefully written, friendly novel that one could read without intermission. The story might easily extract loud laughter, move one to tears, and fill the heart with sympathy for the narrator and the three lost souls who unfold before our eyes\" (a review by Golan, Avirma in ''Ha\u2019Aretz'' newspaper, 9 May 2001). \n*2006: ''The Lion, his Mane and the Giraffe''. Tel Aviv: Am Oved. A humorous children's book, carrying hidden autobiographical elements, which presents the relationship between a giraffe and a lion after the lion has shaved his mane. It is a story on a true friendship, changes and personal identity.\n*2008: ''The Octopus and the Sea Horse''. Tel Aviv: Am Oved. Children's book on a young octopus with itchy tentacles which get him in trouble, until he finds a friend.\n*2009: ''Into the Fullness of the Void: A Spiritual Autobiography''. (2007; 2013) USA: Jewish Lights Publishers, Tel Aviv: Am Oved. Dov Elbaum grew up in an ultra-Orthodox Jerusalem family, and was a prodigy who seemed destined for greatness in the world of Talmud study. But in his late teens, he abruptly broke away and set off into secular Israeli society. In this fascinating, courageous and compelling autobiography, Elbaum seeks to understand his decision and its consequences. With the structure of Kabbalah as his road map, Elbaum journeys into the deep recesses of his self and his soul. This is an intimate, honest, revealing work, both deeply personal and strikingly universal. The Hebrew edition was a bestseller and sold over 50,000 copies.  \"Brilliant, courageous and innovative.\u2026 Serves as a modern continuation of the literary and scholarly work of Martin Buber [and] follows in the footsteps of Abraham Joshua Heschel\u2019s work.\u2026 Makes present and internalizes the ancient Kabbalistic perceptions in his personal life [and] creates a renewed understanding\u2014both personal and spiritual\u2014of a Jewish tradition that today non-Jews and non-Israelis worldwide are also fascinated by.\" (a review by Moshe Idel, Max Cooper Professor of Jewish Thought, Hebrew University, Jerusalem). \n*2012: ''The Eagle\u2019s Island''. Tel Aviv: Am Oved. A fairy tale inspired by the story of Rabbi Nachman of Breslov. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n* {{official|http://www.dovelbaum.com/ }}\n* Mitch Ginsburg, [https://web.archive.org/web/20070709173918/http://www.bina.org.il/event/tikshoret/elbom/elbom_2apr2007.pdf/ The Hiloni Rebbe], ''The Jerusalem Report'', 2 April, 2007.\n* Beth Kissileff, [http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/163824/ex-frum-vs-datlash-two-very-different-literary-genres/ \u2018Ex-Frum\u2019 vs. \u2018Datlash:\u2019 Two Very Different Literary Genres],''The Scroll'', 24 February, 2014.\n* [http://hartman.org.il/Faculty_View.asp?faculty_id=155&Cat_Id=333&Cat_Type=About/ Shalom Hartman Institute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140310022111/http://www.jewishlights.com/page/product/978-1-58023-715-4 Into the Fullness of the Void] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131224121012/http://www.bina.org.il/en/programs/yeshiva/about BINA]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/events/592591867463001/?source=1/ Dov Elbaum North America Book Tour March 21- April 1 2014] \n* [https://www.facebook.com/DovElbaumpage/ Dov Elbaum Facebook Page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elbaum, Dov}}\n[[Category:Israeli editors]]\n[[Category:Israeli journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of Judaism]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University alumni]]\n[[Category:Tel Aviv University faculty]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Adi Lautman Interdisciplinary Programme for Outstanding Students]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dov Elbaum.jpg|thumbnail|Dov Elbaum]]\n'''Dov Elbaum''' ({{lang-he|\u05d3\u05d1 \u05d0\u05dc\u05d1\u05d5\u05d9\u05dd}}; born on 21 December 1970) is an [[Israel]]i writer, editor, journalist, television host and Jewish philosophy lecturer.  \n\n==Biography==\nDov Elbaum was born in Jerusalem's [[Mea She'arim]] neighborhood to an ultra-Orthodox Jewish family. Elbaum is a fifth generation scion of Rabbi [[Yosef Chaim Sonnenfeld]]. He grew up in [[Ramat Eshkol]].<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/weekend/magazine/confessions-of-a-religious-anarchist-in-israel-1.428080 Confessions of a religious anarchist, ''[[Haaretz]]]''</ref> He studied at the ultra-Orthodox [[Hebron Yeshiva]] but left the yeshiva and religion after realizing that he did not want to live with the restrictions and isolation from society imposed by the yeshiva's brand of Orthodoxy. After his renunciation of a religious lifestyle, his father cut off contact with him for ten years.<ref>[http://www.jpost.com/Magazine/Books/Filling-the-void-339143 Filling the void], ''[[Jerusalem Post]]''</ref> He served in the [[Israel Defense Forces]] as a journalist for ''BaMahaneh'', the IDF's weekly magazine. He studied at the [[Adi Lautman Interdisciplinary Programme for Outstanding Students]] of [[Tel-Aviv University]], where he earned an interdisciplinary BA in Philosophy, Kabbalah and Hassidism, and an MA with a research focus on Rabbi [[Nachman of Breslov]]. \n\nElbaum is married to Carmit, has four daughters and lives in [[Kokhav Yair]].\n\n==Journalism and media career==\nFrom 1993-2000, Elbaum wrote extensively for two newspapers, ''Hadashaot'' and ''Yediot Ahronot''. In 2006, he served as editor-in-chief of ''Yediot Ahronot Publishers'' and edited the publisher's flagship project ''People of the Book'', a series celebrating Israel's 60th anniversary. He has edited works by [[Martin Buber]], [[Gershom Scholem]] and others. Elbaum left ''Yediot Ahronot'' Publishers to spend more time writing. He is the author of three novels, ''Zman Elul'' (1997; 2003), ''My Life with the Ancestors'' (2001) and ''Into the Fullness of the Void'' (2007;2009). he has also written three children\u2019s books and numerous essays.\n\nElbaum wrote the script for the weekly television show ''[[Parashat Hashavua]]'' (The Weekly Torah Portion) hosted by Gil Kopatch on channel 1 in 1997. Two years later he wrote the script for the film ''Zakota'', which was broadcast as part of the Wolgin competition at the Jerusalem Film Festival, and aired numerous times on channel 2. This script won first prize of the Council of Culture and Arts of the Ministry of Education.{{CN|date=December 2013}} Between 2001-2005 Elbaum conducted over 700 interviews in the award-winning program, ''Hotzeh Israel'' (